s of people – the Chief Executive Officers of major companies. Interest in the behavior and thinking of CEOs is not confined to their corporation’s direct stakeholders only, the public is increasingly interested in how CEO’s stand on current issues and community debate. Through case study analysis of companies such as News Corporation, BP, Wells Fargo, Satyam, Uber, Canadian National Railway, Tesla, and Boeing, authors Russell Craig and Joel Amernic illustrate ways of mining meaning or decoding a CEO’s written words and speeches. They critically examine a variety of public media, including social media, testimony, and speeches, performed by leaders of major companies. Decoding CEO-Speak demonstrates how monitoring the language of CEOs can yield valuable insights to a company’s policy, strategy, and ethicality; and how it can point to the priorities, values, and personality of the CEO. The book will appeal to CEOs, senior managers, and public relations and media consultants, as well as business professors, students, and corporate stakeholders who want to find otherwise disguised meaning in the words of leaders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChief executive officersxLanguagevCase studies. 0aCorporate culturevCase studies. 0aDiscourse analysisxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Management.2bisacsh  aaccountability.  achief executive officer.  acorporate reporting.  aethics.  alanguage.  aleadership.  amanagement.  amarketing.  apublic relations.  astrategy.  atone at the top.  atwitter.1 aAmernic, Joel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z97831107392200 cprintz978148750595040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753301440uh